      },
      "date": "2020-09-12 15:30:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nwhat about a memory barrier that the spinlock provides? I know it's not needed on x86, but on the other architectures?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f94f1823d3a4fe75174468ce45828ff8e382f5b1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2020-09-17 00:30:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> what about a memory barrier that the spinlock provides?\n\nWhat about it?\nThere is no nearby code that accesses any shared data that might change, so there is nothing that this access needs to be ordered with respect to.\n\nIf this read happens when other other CPU is writing, there are three possibilities:\n1/ the read gets the value from before the write happened.\n2/ the read gets the value from after the write happened.\n3/ the read gets a value that was corrupted by an incomplete write.\n\n1 and 2 are true whether there is a spinlock in use or not.\n3/ can happen with 64-bit values on a 32-bit platform, but for values that fit into the machine word, this is not possible.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
